 DE\n| align=\"center\"| [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2017 NFL Draft|2017]]\n| align=\"center\"| 7\n| align=\"center\"| 14\n| align=\"center\"| 232\n| align=\"center\"| {{sortname|Elijah|Lee}}\n| align=\"center\"| LB\n| align=\"center\"| [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2018 NFL Draft|2018]]\n| align=\"center\"| 5\n| align=\"center\"| 5\n| align=\"center\"| 142\n| align=\"center\"| {{sortname|D.J.|Reed}}\n| align=\"center\"| DB\n| align=\"center\"| [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 NFL Draft|2019]]\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| align=\"center\"| 41\n| align=\"center\"| {{sortname|Dalton|Risner}}\n| align=\"center\"| OT\n| align=\"center\"| [[Denver Broncos]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2019 NFL Draft|2019]]\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| align=\"center\"| 32\n| align=\"center\"| 205\n| align=\"center\"| {{sortname|Duke|Shelley}}\n| align=\"center\"| DB\n| align=\"center\"| [[Chicago Bears]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable undrafted players==\nA selection of notable KSU football players who entered the NFL outside the draft includes:\n:* [[Bert Pearson (American football)|Bert Pearson]] entered the NFL in 1929, before the draft began.  In an eight-year career with the [[Chicago Bears]] he was part of two NFL championship teams.\n:* [[Doug Russell (American football)|Doug Russell]] entered the NFL in 1934, before the draft began.  He [[List of National Football League rushing champions|led the league in rushing]] in the [[1935 NFL season]], playing for the [[Chicago Cardinals]].\n:* [[Paul Coffman]] entered the NFL as an undrafted [[free agent]] in 1978.  He earned three [[Pro Bowl]] appearances during his career and is in the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]].\n:* [[Damian Johnson (American football)|Damian Johnson]] entered the NFL as an undrafted free agent in 1986 and played for the New York Giants' [[Super Bowl XXI]]-winning team.\n:* [[Kendyl Jacox]] entered the NFL as an undrafted free agent in 1998.  He had a nine-year NFL career, starting 93 games on the offensive line.\n:* [[Ryan Lilja]] entered the NFL as an undrafted free agent in 2004. He had an eight-year NFL career, starting in 104 games on the offensive line and playing for the Indianapolis Colts [[Super Bowl XLI]] winning team.\n\nNine KSU players were selected by other leagues directly challenging the NFL: two were drafted in the 1948 [[All-America Football Conference]] draft ([[Rollin Prather]] and Mike Zeleznek),<ref name=KSUdraft/><ref>{{Cite web|title=1948 AAFC Draft |publisher=profootballarchives.com |url=http://www.profootballarchives.com/1948AAFCDraft.html |accessdate=2013-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IBDdSvum?url=http://www.profootballarchives.com/1948AAFCDraft.html |archivedate=July 17, 2013 }}</ref> two were selected in the [[1983 USFL Draft]] (Amos Donaldson and Will Cokeley), three were selected in the [[1984 USFL Draft]] (Reggie Singletary, L. E. Madison and Eric Mack), and two more in the [[1985 USFL Draft]] ([[Eric Bailey (American football)|Eric Bailey]] and Kyle Clawson).  Many of these players also played in the NFL.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|College football|Kansas|Lists}}\n* [[List of Kansas State University people]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kansas State Wildcats football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of National Football League draftees by college football team|Kansas State Wildcats]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football players|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Josh Freeman.jpg|thumb|right|Josh Freeman was drafted 17th overall by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in the 2009 NFL Draft.]]\nThis is a list of [[Kansas State Wildcats football]] players drafted into the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and [[American Football League]] (AFL).  Kansas State has had a total of 147 players selected \u2013 including five players taken in the first round \u2013 from the first [[NFL Draft]] in 1936 through the [[2019 NFL Draft]].<ref name=profootballreference>{{Cite web| title = Kansas St. Drafted Players | publisher = pro-football-reference.com | url = https://www.pro-football-reference.com/colleges/kansasst/drafted.htm  | accessdate = 2013-10-28}}</ref><ref name=KSUdraft>{{Citation| title = KSU Football Media Guide | publisher = Kansas State University | url = http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/ksu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2013-14/misc_non_event/2013FootballMediaGuide.pdf | page = 178 | year = 2013 | format = pdf | accessdate = 2013-10-28}}</ref><ref name=NFLdraftsite>{{Cite web| title = NFL.com Draft Tracker | publisher = NFL.com | url = http://www.nfl.com/draft/history/fulldraft?abbr=K&collegeName=Kansas+State&abbrFlag=0&type=school  | accessdate = 2013-10-28}}</ref> Kansas State has an active streak of having at least one player drafted into the NFL for 26 consecutive years (1994\u20132019).\n\nAfter the NFL [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merged]] with the AFL in 1966, the history of the AFL was officially adopted by the NFL and therefore this list includes players taken in the [[American Football League Draft|AFL Draft]] (1960\u20131966) and in the [[Common Draft]] (1967\u20131969) in addition to the NFL Draft.<ref name=NFLdraftsite/>  Once the AFL officially merged with the NFL in 1970, the \"Common Draft\" simply became the NFL Draft. Because four KSU players were selected in both the NFL and AFL drafts, the total number of selections listed below is 151 (including one \"redshirt\" selection in the 1965 AFL Draft), through the 2019 draft.\n\nEach NFL [[Professional sports league organization|franchise]] seeks to add new players through the annual NFL Draft. The [[NFL Draft#Procedure and rules|draft rules]] were last updated in 2009. The team with the worst record the previous year picks first, the next-worst team second, and so on. Teams that did not make the playoffs are ordered by their regular-season record with any remaining ties broken by [[strength of schedule]]. [[NFL Playoffs|Playoff participants]] are sequenced after non-playoff teams, based on their round of elimination (wild card, division, conference, and [[Super Bowl]]).\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| B\n| [[Back (American football)|Back]]\n| K \n| [[Placekicker|Kicker]]\n| NT\n| [[Nose tackle]]\n|-\n| C\n| [[Center (American football)|Center]]\n| LB\n| [[Linebacker]]\n| BB\n| [[Blocking back]]\n|-\n| DB\n| [[Defensive back]]\n| P\n| [[Punter (American football)|Punter]]\n| HB\n| [[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]]\n|-\n| DE\n| [[Defensive end]]\n| QB\n| [[Quarterback]]\n| WR\n| [[Wide receiver]]\n|-\n| DT\n| [[Defensive tackle]]\n| RB\n| [[Running back]]\n| G\n| [[Guard (American football)|Guard]]\n|-\n| E\n| [[End (American football)|End]]\n| T\n| [[Offensive tackle]]\n| TE\n| [[Tight end]]\n|-\n| FB\n| [[Fullback (American football)|Fullback]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFE6BD\" align=\"center\" | *\n| colspan=\"5\" | Selected to a [[Pro Bowl]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#DDFFDD\" align=\"center\" | \u2020\n| colspan=\"5\" | Won a [[List of NFL champions|NFL championship]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#D0E7FF\" align=\"center\" | \u2021\n| colspan=\"5\" | Selected to a Pro Bowl and won an NFL championship\n|-\n|}\n\n==Players selected==\n<!-- IMAGES -->\n[[File:Terence newman.JPG|thumb|right|Terence Newman was drafted 5th overall by the Dallas Cowboys in the 2003 NFL Draft.|alt=An American football player leans forward. He is not wearing pads but is wearing his white jersey over a long-sleeved gray shirt.]]\n[[File:Michael Bishop.jpg|thumb|right|Michael Bishop was drafted in the 7th round by the New England Patriots in the 1999 NFL Draft.|alt=An American football player w